	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> TTT - Many Riddles   Pt.3<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.89)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025'>Brad "Dr_Diablo" Peck</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 16, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
<br />
Well, this will probably be the end of the road for this series of articles.  I may decide to include another article dealing with the set as a whole, and I will look at things like images, new rules and comparisons to older sets.  But enough about the next article, it’s time to focus on this one.  Thankfully I now have had some experience with the cards as I constructed a Rohan/Raider deck and my brother constructed a Ranger/Uruk deck.  I had forgot to mention in my analysis of Gondor that they would be able to use No Stranger To The Shadows, and when facing a twilight denial Ranger deck I was almost forced to double jump every turn, sometimes even past sanctuaries.  As for my shadow side I wanted to try out several of the Raiders, and we made him an Isengard deck similar to his old one, but with an added TTT flavor.  My shadow side was quite helpful in getting me to work around with the new cards, and will really help out the advice I can give.  So without further waiting, here I go again….<br />
<br />
<br />
RAIDERS – Almost as bad as Orcs, and much bigger<br />
<br />
Well, as with Isengard, the Raiders were divided into two major sub-sections – the Southrons and the Easterlings.  Ever since seeing the first picture they released of an Easterling’s armor (way back a few months ago), I knew that was the culture I wanted to play.  The Southrons I seemed less encouraged to try, but I must say, the Oliphaunts look awesome in some of their pictures.  The Raiders were probably meant to be mixed together, as certain Southrons benefit from burdens which the Easterlings can place on the Ring-Bearer, and the Easterlings would greatly benefit from some Southron cards that add twilight to the pool.  Neither of these cultures struck me too much as one that would achieve a lot on the tournament scene alone, but together or mixed with another culture they would surely help out.  <br />
<br />
EASTERLINGS – Burdening aplenty<br />
<br />
Well, I tried out an Easterling/Nazgul deck for my first TTT shadow side.  Burdening has never been the top shadow side in my area, and even though several people have tried it, they usually end up going back to a skirmishing shadow side.  I figured it was at least worth a try.  Now my shadow side would probably had worked better against my brother had he not used Ring-bound guys to skirmish them, and since he knew to bid zero in the beginning.  But regardless I used many of the available Easterlings (though there aren’t very many).  It also probably didn’t help that I only got 1 Skirmisher and 1 Captain from the boxes.  Anyways, so the deck was constructed with 4 Lieutenants, 4 Guards, 3 Axemen, and 1 of each Captain and Skirmisher, backed up with a pair of Twilight Witch-kings and non-twilight Toldeas and Enqueas.  The deck did work well to slow him down, but I found that the Easterlings just didn’t have the support yet to get down the burdens.  Ieasterlinguard or Lieutenant is forced to take a wound due to archery or fighting a mounted companion, they are almost useless.  The Captain requires you to have a lot of spare twilight, as due most of the events I tried playing.  I found rarely that I had enough left over twilight for the Men of Rhun or New Fear, so Decipher is going to have to work on some way for them (as a stand-alone sub-culture) to work.  Don’t get me wrong, they will be able to put some burdens down, but it just doesn’t seem like they were tweaked enough to be used completely independently.   Using a few other cultures (or Southrons) that benefit from burdens will be a key to success, but I don’t think that Easterlings will be promising success any time soon.  Give them another set and they will be a great deal better.<br />
<br />
SOUTHRONS – Twilight Managing 101<br />
<br />
From a story-line point of view, I expected the Southrons to have a much different aspect of gameplay.  As far as my memory goes (which isn’t the greatest) the Southrons were only seen in three spots during the Lord of the Rings books.  The first, and seemingly pre-dominant, is their help to Isengard in the attack on Helm’s Deep.  The second, and last time we see them, is in the siege on Gondor, but we’ll be waiting a year or so for that set to come out.  The third, and something I was hoping would have been implicated, was the scene where Faramir and his rangers intercept a group of Southrons heading to Isengard to help in the battle.  Seeing the way the new Gondor rangers are structured, I hope they realize that one shadow culture or another should be a counter to the opponent playing Gondor.  There was very little in their that affected a Ring-bound opponent.  This is nothing against the culture or the people at Decipher that made the cards, but it’s my own personal viewpoint.  The Southrons require you to have a phenomenal sense of twilight management, as most of their conditions, events and minions are going to need you to have twilight after the assignment phase is finished.  The Desert dwellers (Soldier, Spearman, Warrior) are all simply the “expansive Hate” guys: they pay 3 twilight to wound the character they are skirmishing.  This is useful if you can get a lot of twilight to the pool, but if your opponent either denies you twilight, or can prevent wounds, they are a lost cause for twilight.  Thankfully, the event Flanking Attack is there to give conveniently 3 twilight, so at least you can catch your opponent by surprise with it.  The only thing I see these Desert guys good for is when your opponent has some exhausted companions.  The same ability also comes from the Soutron Spear and Whirling Strike, so it may be easier to use other Southrons with these two cards.  The next group of Southrons is the archers, who unlike the Isengard archers, do guided exertions.  This isn’t necessarily bad, but for the same price you could play Uruk archers and get guided wounds (unless you were going for the Raider theme, then by all means use these guys).  The only reason I see to play Southron archers is to use Arrow From the South, which lets you heal them during the archery phase so you can let them shoot again and Rapid Fire, which lets one little archer cause a lot of wounds.  The one thing I will admit I like about the Southrons is that they have several minions which spot a certain number of companions to assign the minion to the Ring-bearer.  Southron Wanderer spots 5 companions to do this, and adds 4 twilight if the Free Peoples player chooses not to, which is helpful because of the high cost of all the events you’ll need to play.  Similar to this is the Southron Commander who spots 6 companions, and discards an unbound companion if not assigned, and the beastly Southron Troop which spots 7, and lets you discard a companion if not assigned.  Now as much as their game text sounds like it would kill the opponents guys quickly, you have to wonder have many people are going to be playing any more than 5 companions now.  Regardless, I suggest throwing in a Commander just for surprise if the opponent decides to play a large Fellowship.<br />
<br />
The Raiders as a whole aren’t spectacular.  They have their ups and they have their downs, but to me the downs seem a lot heavier than the ups.  One thing I have noticed though, and it is definitely something worth noticing, is the card Eastern Emyn Muil.  This card needs to be played at site 2, so you have to get it in your starting hand, or after your first Free Peoples turn (if you go first).  Combining this with the site Western Emyn Muil will prove devastating to any Ring-bound deck, and if your opponent is playing all or mainly unbound companions, well, at least you got a few exertions out of Frodo.  After site 2 it can be used for exerting a Ring-bound companion once, so it isn’t too bad afterwards either.  If you are given enough twilight, you could finish off a Ring-bound deck once they move from site two, and this card is not restricted to Raiders, but if you don’t draw it first turn, it is useless for other cultures.<br />
<br />
Raider cards to use in any deck:<br />
Well, the list isn’t too long, since they seem made to work entirely with one another.  <br />
Ithilien Wilderness: Should make it into every multi-player deck.<br />
Desert Legion: Could work in a Nazgul burdening deck, an Uruk Worry deck, or anything that burdens.<br />
Easterling Captain: It’s your call on this guy, but at least he can pump his power up a lot if you have the twilight for it.<br />
Southron Scout:Could make their way into a Moria deck…. I don’t know I’m struggling to find a card worth using outside of making a Raider deck.<br />
EASTERN EMYN MUIL!!!!!!!!!!<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
ROHAN – Hello, I’m Eomer and I’ve come to haul some @$$!!!!<br />
<br />
Ahhh, finally I get to the Rohan.  I like this culture because not only are they tough in the book/movie, but the three main Rohan companions (Eomer, Eowyn and Theoden) were designed really well.  The entire culture was designed really well actually, as they had to figure out something for horses to do besides adding to power.  The forced exertions they cause are both a blessing and a curse.  Now it’s obvious as to why they are a blessing, but you are probably wondering why they are a curse.  Well, if you rely too much on them too much, possession discards may eat them alive and they become wasted cards (not to mention more cards in case you fear Grima) that have no effect on either Moria or Dunland, as with a few other minions here and there.  But, they are still worth the effort of playing because of the game texts of Elite Riders and the rare Eomer.  I think Eomer was possibly the most useful card and most thought out card in the entire set.  Of course he’s only useful when given his possessions, but in my opinion, the direction they took with boosting him because of the horses couldn’t be any more fitting.  Enough praise about him, why don’t I go into why he is good.  Versus the popular Uruk-Hai and Nazgul decks, he is a machine, getting at least +2 strength in battle, more if you have archery or some way of exerting minions.  With Firefoot and his Spear he is probably one of the toughest characters to kill along with loaded up Aragorn and Gandalf.  Wearing both he gets defender +1 and damage +2, plus becomes power plus 2 for each wound on the character he is skirmishing, getting at least one from the horse, and possibly more from archery or exertions.  Eowyn has two versions that are both good, but each one is useful in a different way.  The rare Eowyn allows you to add to the pool to save her once she becomes exhausted, which is definitely your choice is she is going to be one of your attackers.  The common one, and my personal favourite, is useful when she is a back-up fighter, as she can absorb the wounds off your main fighters.  As for her equipment, her sword is a surprising strength +3 and damage +1 (when you spot a villager), which will make her able to fight smaller minions with ease.  Finally for main companions we have Theoden, who again is given two choices for which to use, both that are dependant on different decks.  The common Theoden allows you to liberate sites which will obviously be useful if your opponent plans to take control of sites, and the Starter deck Theoden allows you to heal up your guys once a turn when you play a possession on them.  I suggest playing at least a copy of each in your deck, so you can have a bit of time to decide which is better, since you’ll most likely be playing the site 3 that allows you to draw him.  His equipment and support cards are absolutely worth using him as a tank.  Firstly, his sword Herugrim adds 2 strength and 1 vitality, and makes him damage +1.  Not bad, but he’s still only at 3 vitality.  Hearken To Me (yes I know it’s a Gandalf condition, I just felt like mentioning it again) lets you add another 2 strength and 1 vitality, and removes any possibility of the opponent throwing shadow conditions on him.  And finally Theoden is given his armor, the King’s Mail, which lets him take only 1 wound during each skirmish, and prevents wounds in any other phase.  This will let Theoden tank a lot of big hits, or dish out a few of his own.  Keep in mind that with Grima bound to be seen everywhere, Theoden may only want to use two of these cards, just in case.  The Elite Riders are a lesser version of Eomer, but would still make for a killer deck given that the opponent isn’t using swarms.  <br />
<br />
But that should be enough about the companions to convince you of how good they are.  Let us move on to the support cards.  The allies for Rohan are quite useful if you are building a mainly-Rohan deck, as there are 2 each of healers and strength adders.  One of each is generally for a Rohan companion, and the other is for a mounted companion, so you could heal or pump Gandalf on Shadowfax if you wished.  But the best ally by far is Aldor, as he can spot a villager to exert and add one to the archery total.  Now one archery honestly doesn’t sound too good at all, but try to remember, this is Rohan we’re talking about, and they’ve always got a little something up there sleeve.  So you put one lousy archery wound on a minion, lets say a nice 3 vitality Uruk.  Now you go and assign him to Eomer, who throws another exertion (leaving the minion with two wounds) and making Eomer strength +4.  Sure, it’s not A Ranger’s Versatility or anything broken like that, but it will help to win skirmishes, I can tell you that.  The allies have some support cards, and helpers too.  Well Stored allows you to heal an ally at the start of each turn. Fight for the Villagers allows a strength bonus of 3 to a Rohan Man if you spot an ally.  Vallys of the Mark (sticking to the exertion theme) lets you exert a roaming minion when played, which will help get you to site 4 very quickly.  Fortress Never Fallen can be used for condition removal as you know you’ll certainly win a few skirmishes.  Helm! Helm! can be used as a method of drawing cards during the regroup to prepare for a double move, or for site liberation if you are using the healing version of Theoden.  But possibly the best Rohan support card comes in the form of a flower.  Simbelmyne allows you to play only a copy of each possession you need as you can search through your deck for any Rohan possession or character.  This card will be huge for Rohan, and be sure to see a couple copies in each Rohan deck.  <br />
<br />
I think I’ve exhausted what I wanted to say about Rohan, as they were only given 35 cards anyways.  They are a very good culture to play, and it’s fun to see your opponent squirm as Eomer takes down there biggest minions.  Rohan decks must be built almost entirely out of Rohan culture cards, but when playing these decks, be sure to add a Proper Poet and a Ranger of the North for a bit of late game protection.<br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
Eomer/Spear/Firefoot:  He’s a beast.  Do I need to say more?<br />
Eowyn, Lady of Rohan: Great for fodder as she can prevent wounds in other skirmishes, and then be killed off in another.<br />
Brego: Hey it’s a cheap way to heal your guy, and exert your opponent’s minion.  I thought of throwing this on Faramir and using this and his bow to kill off things.  This is only a test idea thus far, but try it.  Only problem is you must spot a Rohan Man, so it may be for mixed fellowships only.<br />
<br />
<br />
THE SHIRE CULTURE – <br />
<br />
Firstly, I guess I should talk about the new versions of the Hobbit companions, and tell you why you would want to discard your own minions.  When I originally read the spoilers I thought to myself “Now why on Middle-Earth would I want to discard my Hobbit companions?” and it puzzled me for quite some time.  But after feeling like a huge idiot, it hit me.  I wasn’t killing them off, I was discarding them.  It all made sense now from both a gameplay and storyline point of view.  Merry and Pippin distracted the attention from Frodo so the Uruks followed them at Amon Hen.  In the game they are doing very much the same thing.  The rare Merry will be almost useless until a year from now when the Return of the King set comes out and we are given almost every minion being from the Sauron culture.  The common Merry I like for a few reasons.  If you have exhausted Frodo through some means of exertion or wound taking, and are using the Son of Drogo version, you can exert Merry to heal Frodo up and then discard him.  He can also fight that skirmish you really don’t want to kill off Sam or Frodo in.  Pippin is very much the same, but the rare version lets you discard him if he’s not assigned to remove an Uruk-Hai from a skirmish, and the common version lets you add a burden to discard him.  Both these Hobbits seem rather strange, and you would figure you would need a lot of cards to keep them going, but in truth, this strategy relies on very little.  The rare Gandalf and Treebeard of this set allow you to bring the back from the discard pile (or from Treebeard himself), and the Shire card Knocked On The Head allows you to get them back as well.  The event Warmed Up A Bit can be used to discard them if you would rather not pay the price of an exertion or a burden.  Now for this strategy of discarding the two I am kind of concerned that it will not work.  I have yet to hear of decks based on discarding Hobbits, but the unbound Hobbits sure have a good deck in store for them.  The new versions of Aragorn, Legolas and Gimli designed to work with unbound Hobbits provide a very fun and very “story-following” type of deck.  However, I don’t see either new version of Merry being used, and possibly the rare Pippin, as Uruks will still be in dominance.<br />
<br />
Now on to our Ring-bound Hobbits – Frodo and Sam.  Frodo, Tired Traveller  was almost designed solely to be used in a Ring-bound rangers deck.  Each time you play a Ring-bound companion, you may remove a burden (only in the Fellowship phase though, sorry no starters).  This allows you to bid high to go first for your rangers deck, but has little use besides that.  Frodo, Courteous Halfling was designed in case discard is heavy in your meta.  Decipher seems to have looked at two things when making this set – what was the meta like prior to the set and how do we counter what was over-played, and how do we follow the story line to a certain extent, while still keeping cards powerful.  Anyways, now on to Samwise, my personal favourite character from the books.  Samwise the Brave is very similar to the original common version of Sam, except he only has to exert once to cancel a card adding burdens.  There’s a plus in him only having to exert once, but there’s a downfall too, in that he has to exert right when the burden is about to be added and he cannot remove burdens from himself should he become the Ring-bearer.  I have no clue so far which would be better, but I’m still planning on Proper Poet being used instead of either.  Sam, Frodo’s Gardener allows you to pull his Pack out of your deck, which then allows you to add two twilight to heal a Ring-bound companion.  This isn’t so bad if the opponent is using Orcs, and you have Sting out, but otherwise you will be giving them a lot of twilight, which is the last thing you want with a couple Hobbits out.  These versions of Frodo and Sam are useful under certain circumstances, but don’t expect them to replace Reluctant Adventurer and Proper Poet for the time being.<br />
<br />
Now on to the Hobbit support cards.  One card thus far is already referred to as broken, and that is the Cliffs of Emyn Muil.  This card allows you to get rid of some burdens if you grab it first turn, and is a mini-PATHS (though you discard it instead of adding a burden) you can use at any time.  Now this card does seem a little more powerful then most in the deck, but ultimately it isn’t broken.  It is nice however when you want to get rid of a two vitality minion skirmishing Frodo (one wound from PATHS, another from this), or is great versus Moria or Dunland.  And thankfully unlike PATHS you don’t have to hold one in your hand until you need it.<br />
<br />
Escape hit me as another card I would want to use, though not too much for the gametext, but more for the extra vitality.  This means that Merry from the Fellowship set can add his power twice to a companion, or once to two different companions.  It’s also useful in an all-Hobbit deck if you want to make Pippin your exertions took (since no versions of his have much reason for exerting).  Too bad it’s only for play on unbound Hobbit, but otherwise is would be broken beyond belief.  The new Hobbit Intuition and Stealth, fine I’ll call them Swiftly and Softly and Severed His Bonds, are quite good except that they are no longer power adders (but the original two were too powerful anyways).  Most of the new cards have not much that I can talk about for too long as most are rather self-explanatory, but let’s just say you better have some burden removal if you want to use a lot of these.  One thing you may want to use with this is Frodo’s Cloak as it can be used to cancel skirmishes, or heal and remove a burden.  The canceling of skirmishes isn’t too important with other cards that allow for that, but healing both a wound and a burden is great, as you can do it several times with different copies of the cloak.<br />
<br />
Cards worth using:<br />
Cliffs of Emyn Muil: Rather broken, so they’ll help out a good number of decks.<br />
Get On and Get Away: Thror’s Map for people who like burdens.<br />
Light Shining Faintly: Provide some form of healing to Ring-bound ranger decks, or Sam.<br />
Swiftly and Softly: Can get you past site 5 with little trouble in skirmishes.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
THE SITE PATH – When Moria and Nazgul lose, Raiders and Dunland gain<br />
<br />
All right, I’m not sure how exactly to explain the sites very well.  Most of them are rather explanatory of themselves, but heck, I’ll give it a shot.<br />
<br />
SITE 1<br />
East Wall of Rohan: Useful if you still want to try our Nazgul (as you’ll get more early twilight if they double move), or if you just want to tempt the opponent to move only once on their first turn.<br />
<br />
Eastemnet Downs: This is for those people that like to play all the companions they are starting with (Frodo alone, Frodo and Aragorn, Frodo and Gandalf, whatever….).  If you play a small number of companions in your deck, this may be useful, but it looks like it could hurt you too.<br />
<br />
Eastemnet Gullies: Hard to tell the uses for this one.  Firstly, any Elf deck could start Arwen and someone else (Haldir probably) and go for Legolas first turn.  Unbound Hobbits will likely start Legolas and go for Aragorn first turn.<br />
<br />
Horse-country: Honestly, it says horse in the title.  There’s little question as to which culture this is going to help.  Move limit +1 is always good, but I don’t know how much you want to move to site 4 on turn 1.<br />
<br />
Plains of Rohan: Only should be used for Dwarven decks, as he’ll start in a Three Hunters deck, and will be used in multiple copies or not at all in an unbound Hobbits deck.  If you find another use for pulling Gimli instead of starting him, I’d really like to know.<br />
<br />
The Riddermark: The Prancing Pony with a price to pay.  I am a little curious as to why this came in the Aragorn starter since you were supposed to start Aragorn in it, but whatever. (Yes, I know people started Gimli and Legolas, but it’s an Aragorn “starter” so you should “start” Aragorn.  And yes, I am picky)<br />
<br />
Western Emyn Muil: As I said in the Raiders section, this site and the condition Eastern Emyn Muil is just a dirty thing to play. <br />
<br />
SITE 2<br />
Derndingle: Again (see Horse-country) there is little reason to move so far on your first turn unless your opponent decided a shadow side without minions would be the best way to go…. and now my eyes are rolling.<br />
<br />
Eastfold: Well, it’s simple.  Are you playing Uruk trackers? You are? Ok, then use this site.  There, simple.<br />
<br />
Fangorn Forest: I like Treebeard in the book.  He’s interesting, and seems rather horny for the Ent-wives (ok, not really).  The cards however don’t interest me that much.  Play this site is you have unbound discarding Hobbits in the deck, or you want a 12 power ally at site 8.<br />
<br />
Plains of Rohan Camp: Play this only if you think you are going to get beaten like hell on the first move.  It’s a nice back-up plan, but it’s really not that great if it’s only at site 2.<br />
<br />
Rohirrim Village: Well, here’s another toughy.  Are you playing Dunland? Wait, you are? Ok, use this site.  Gee, what will I think of for the site three that does the same thing…<br />
<br />
Uruk Camp: This site is especially helpful when playing Eomer or archery since it gets an exertion on any Uruk played.  This at least will let you play a few cards and not worry about too many minons coming down first turn.<br />
<br />
Wold of Rohan: It interested me to know that Wold was a word, as I hadn’t heard it before.  This site is a blessing and a curse to use, as it will give you some more twilight to use against the opponent, but will give them more to use against you.  And if they can use it better, you’ll probably kick yourself.<br />
<br />
SITE 3<br />
Barrows of Edoras: I like the fact that you can play every card from your hand that’s a Free Peoples card, and then drop whatever is left to draw four more cards.  Useful if you have some quick playing Free Peoples cards like possessions or conditions, or you get stuck with a weak Fellowship and a lot of shadow cards.<br />
<br />
Golden Hall: Killer if you can get it to work.  By the time the Fellowship gets here there aren’t usually many possessions, but at least if they are lucky with their draws, they’ll be unlucky when they get here.  This usually keeps me bidding to go second with my Rohan deck, as I can’t afford to lose a possession.<br />
<br />
Stables: Better to play Throne Room, unless you are starting Theoden (which you probably shouldn’t since you can pull him out here anyways).<br />
<br />
Streets of Edoras: Again not too useful as you probably haven’t got that many Rohan allies out, if you are even playing Rohan decks.<br />
<br />
Throne Room: Great site for your Rohan deck, or if playing a large Fellowship you can guarantee to get another guy out quickly.<br />
<br />
Westemnet Plains: Alright now what should I say about this?  I could say “See Rohirrim Village” but that would be too easy.  Hmmm, maybe I have it.  Do you like your Dunland minions that are currently in the deck you are playing to die to archery wounds?  I didn’t think you did.  And even if your opponent isn’t playing archery, isn’t it better to be safe? I think it is.  So you might want to ignore this site completely in your Dunland deck.  Ahh, biting sarcasm – where would I be without thee?<br />
<br />
SITE 4<br />
Ok, here’s where things really begin to happen.  Many minions have stopped roaming, the twilight numbers are growing quickly, and your are going to start facing the full effect of your opponent’s deck if you haven’t yet started.  The Uruks lose something big with the absence of Hollin, Moria loses several of the site 4’s which helped it out and Nazgul lose the site that added a burden.  But Decipher had to move on from those cultures.  Site 4’s in TTT are very targetted towards either helping or hurting the Rohan fellowship.<br />
<br />
Ered Nimrais: Well, this is another site for those of you that wish to start with all the companions you’ll be using.  A twilight cost of +2 per companion and ally is huge if the opponent really needs them, and the extra twilight will be extremely helpful when they get to site 5 which already has a huge twilight number.  This site would most help the Uruks, as you could force them to stop at 4 (if you’re lucky), and if they need re-enforcement before moving to site 5, they would give you the chance to play a few more Uruks. <br />
<br />
Westemnet Hills: I question the uses of this site.  When the fellowship moves here, heal mounted companions and allies.  This site would be better were it not right after a sanctuary, because if you have wounds to heal after the sanctuary you probably should build another Rohan deck.<br />
<br />
White Mountains: This site is much better for Rohan than the Westemnet Hills nonsense.  Given that you have a site 3 which lets you pull Theoden out, you probably won’t hurt yourself by using this site.  Sure, Theo’s got to face an exertion, but you should be able to figure out a way to heal that off him.  Plus, if your opponent isn’t playing him, they’ll have a much more difficult time making it by site 5 without feeling too much damage.<br />
<br />
White Rocks: The choice for many non-Rohan decks.  This site won’t do terribly much by itself, as you would add maybe another 2 or 3 twilight tops.  But, looking at the overall picture of the game, this would make a double-move a lot harder, as there will be a lot of twilight left for you.  And if the opponent isn’t playing Rohan then there’s really no loss since none of the other sites are going to help you too much.<br />
<br />
SITE 5<br />
Thankfully there’s now a choice for which site 5 to play.  The Bridge was good, don’t get me wrong, but it became tiring seeing it every game.  At least this way there is more customizing allowed for your deck.<br />
<br />
Deep of Helm: This site is an Uruk-Hai deck’s dream.  Essentially you can get your big guys out without having to pay for them.  A 4 cost Lurtz.  Ouch!  And the site already has a twilight number of six, so this is where you want to make the opponent feel the heat.  It’s also a battleground (thoughts of Star Wars CCG come to mind) so you can make benefit of the Uruk Assault Band.<br />
<br />
Deeping Wall: 7 twilight from the site is huge at this point.  This is definitely the site for all Dunland decks since Saruman will be important to soak up the archery or pump your guys.  For Uruks it’s slightly less useful since you can be playing cheaper Uruks at Deep of Helm, but if you require Saruman to make your non-fierce Uruks into some fierce beasts, then this would be a better choice.<br />
<br />
Helm’s Gate: Well, I never thought I’d say it, but this site will probably help out Moria most for all shadow sides.  Yes, it’s true, other shadow sides have some nice weapons, but how many get used that much?  And in terms of Moria getting out pretty much every weapon every turn, they will get benefits versus companions without weapons.  This is also useful for any deck that includes weapons for each of your companions, as you will gain bonuses against pretty much every shadow side.<br />
<br />
Hornburg Courtyard: I am expecting to see Aragorn in just about every deck, whether he is the main fighter or the wound absorber, so this site has limited use.  Unless you are planning on figuring out a quick way of killing him off (and if you do, please share) then your site is going to be rather ineffective.<br />
<br />
Hornburg Paclobert: This is a very general site which could be used in just about any deck.  The minus from the minion archery is a nice “just in case it happens” plan, but the addition to fellowship archery can be a killer.  In a Rohan deck it can mean another wound on whoever is fighting Eomer.  In an archer deck, it can mean another wound which forces the opponent to kill off something.  There’s nothing there that will work against you unless you are using Moria or Dunland which would really hate the plus one archery.<br />
<br />
SITE 6<br />
So, you have finally reached the second sanctuary and have plenty of wounds to get rid of, but with these sites you may be ready to take a few more.  Like many other site numbers, I see help for mainly Uruks and Rohan.  <br />
<br />
Caves oeasterlinglarond: Well, this site is underground in case you play Moria.  Sure it’ll work against you if you are playing against Uruks, but getting a cheaper Cave Troll at a sanctuary is a rather nice touch.  As for the Uruks, in case you have someone that just doesn’t seem to be fierce you could remove two twilight to add that last bit of wounding before they heal up.<br />
<br />
Great Hall: Alright, so Eowyn, Theoden and Eomer exhausted themselves on the way home but the opponent felt like throwing down an Uruk or two.  You don’t really want to kill off anyone, and sometimes not even risk getting them killed, so what do you do?  Well with most Rohan decks you are bound to play at least a couple Rohan allies, so just sacrifice them.  Sure it’s bad to lose your allies, but it is far worse to lose your companions.<br />
<br />
Hornburg Armory: This is the site for just about every non-Uruk, non-Rohan deck.  And I’m sure there will be a lot of those (rolling eyes again).  Ok, so it’s nothing great, but it could be helpful if you have yet to get a couple of possessions.<br />
<br />
SITE 7<br />
You’ve healed yourselves at a sanctuary for the last time, so now you begin the road to victory, commonly known as the road of shame.  From now on you’ll be facing everything the opponent has got, so be ready for some big battles and be ready to start filling up the dead pile.<br />
<br />
Cavern Entrance: Wow! This site is huge for Moria.  7 twilight and it’s underground… Now that’s a deal I’m willing to take.  No skirmish abilities or events turns every companion and minion into a common Faramir and will surely break your Fellowship apart if you are relying on skirmish events.  However this site is quite troubling.  The designers wanted to move away from Fellowships bearing a billion possessions by making Grima and Dunland possession discarders, and encourage the use of skirmish events.  So why on earth build a site that goes against that?  Argh, this game is complicated.<br />
<br />
Hornburg Causeway: A nice way to pump up that archery total, as well as hurting any deck that plays a lot of companions.  I say this because most Ring-boung decks will be rather concise, and most characters that are used for fodder are unbound.  <br />
<br />
King’s Room: Ouch, dirty!  If you aren’t playing a Rohan companion you’ll be doing a ton of exertions, which is about the last thing you want from site 7.  This card could mean some serious wreckage to unbound companions.<br />
<br />
SITE 8<br />
Only 2 choices here, and is only useful if you are playing Dunland.<br />
<br />
Ring of Isengard: Massive card drawing potential if you are playing a Dunland swarm with site control.  This will be a great way to make use of No Retreat, as surely some of your minions will make it to the regroup phase.<br />
<br />
Wizard’s Vale: This site will be in every deck that is non-Dunland.  It’s that simple.  If you were playing twilight denial, you are now going to pay for it.  Alright fine, you are only adding 4 more twilight, but that is usually enough to get down another minion or two so this is going to make many people reconsider playing choke decks.<br />
<br />
SITE 9<br />
And you have finally made it to the end of the path.  The game is on the brink of ending, and hopefully your going to survive.  Or if the opponent beat you here, hopefully you will have the final laugh as you lay down an army.  Half of the site 9’s were based on companion totals being over 4, but there’s generally a good reason to use any of these sites.<br />
<br />
Fortress of Orthanc: If you have a way to draw more cards up then you’ll make use of the +2 twilight per companion over 4 you are getting here.  This may not work so well since you’ll need a way to get minions, which will severely limit its play, but if you saved up enough for the end then you should be fun.<br />
<br />
Orthanc Balcony: Well, Saruman never was a quitter.  He’s like an annoying friend that seems to follow you everywhere you go.  Except he doesn’t seem too friendly.  This will probably be Dunland’s choice for a site 9, as with many Uruk decks that want to make use of Keeper of Isengard’s ferocity.  Saruman’s cheap deploy cost makes up for the site having only 8 twilight instead of 9.<br />
<br />
Orthanc Library: This site will be really good if you are spotting a lot of exhausted companions in the Fellowship.  Drawing a card ortwo could give you a couple more minions to throw down, which will give you the advantage if you can get some that are fierce.  As with Fortress, I don’t see this getting too much play either, not because it’s bad, but because it’s not as good as some of the others.<br />
<br />
Palantir Chamber: Ahhhh, here is the site 9 of all site 9s.  Even if the Ring-bearer only has 2 burdens, you can grab a minion that could make the difference.  I would hate to see a deck that got 6 or more burdens pulling three minions out, as that would be quite devastating.  On a personal note, I usually use this with Moria to pull out Ulaire Nertea, who in turn can pull another minion for each companion over four.  This site will let you get out a bunch of guys to overwhelm the Ring-bearer, or at least let you pull a big guy out to kill off the companions and hopefully get you a good fierce skirmish.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Ok, I am honestly pooped.  I think I have written too much, and most of you said “Ahh, forget it” already.  If you have read this far you probably need to pick up a hobby, but I still thank you for reading my work. I still have a lot to say of the new set, and have decided to wait another week before typing this much again.  My next article will look at everything I promised at the top of this article that it would.  Now I must go to sleep and rest my aching fingers, for 9 pages of Microsoft Word is not a little by any means.  Thanks again for reading.  <br />
